  RELATIONS:
  - TYPE: Parent

[TEXT]
STATEMENT: >>>
This document specifies the functional requirements for Terminfo Database Parsing
(feature id TERMINFO, Tier 4). The feature reads the compiled terminfo binary database
file (ncurses format) to extract terminal capabilities that are authoritative inputs to
the Termicap color detection cascade.

The primary capabilities of interest are: `colors` (numeric — maximum number of colors
supported), `setaf`/`setab` (string — ANSI color-setting escape sequences for foreground
and background), and the user-defined extended capabilities `RGB` and `Tc` (boolean/string
flags that signal truecolor support in tmux-style terminfo extensions).

The parser locates the correct terminfo file by reading the `TERM` environment variable,
then searching the standard directory hierarchy: `$TERMINFO`, each directory in
`$TERMINFO_DIRS`, `~/.terminfo`, `/usr/share/terminfo`, `/etc/terminfo`,
`/lib/terminfo`. Within each directory the file is sought at
`<dir>/<first-char-of-TERM>/<TERM>` (standard ncurses layout on most Unix systems) and,
as a fallback, `<dir>/<two-hex-digits-of-first-char>/<TERM>` (used by some BSDs and
older Solaris installations).

The ncurses compiled terminfo binary format consists of a fixed-size header followed by
five data sections: names, booleans, numerics, strings (including a string table), and an
optional extended (user-defined) section. Two format variants are supported:
  - Legacy (magic 0x011A): numeric fields are 16-bit signed integers.
  - Extended-numeric (magic 0x021E): numeric fields are 32-bit signed integers.

This feature has no FFI dependency. All parsing is pure Ada operating on an in-memory
byte array loaded by a thin file-read binding. The binary parser shall be SPARK Silver
provable: no exceptions, bounded loops, and pre/post contracts on all public operations.
The file-read binding itself shall be declared with SPARK_Mode => Off, consistent with
all other Termicap FFI boundaries.

Integration: the parsed Terminfo_Snapshot record is consumed by the color detection
cascade as a complementary passive source, alongside environment variable heuristics,
to produce or refine the Color_Level result.
<<<

[SECTION]
TITLE: Result Types

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-TIF-001
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Must
TITLE: Terminfo_Snapshot Result Record
STATEMENT: >>>
The library shall provide an immutable record type Terminfo_Snapshot that represents the
subset of a parsed terminfo database entry relevant to Termicap's capability detection.
The record shall contain at minimum:

  Colors         : Integer
    -- Value of the `colors` numeric capability (maximum colors the terminal supports).
    -- -1 (ABSENT_NUMERIC) when the capability is not present in the database entry.
    -- -2 (CANCELLED_NUMERIC) when the capability has been explicitly cancelled.

  Has_Setaf      : Boolean
    -- True when the `setaf` string capability is present and non-empty.

  Has_Setab      : Boolean
    -- True when the `setab` string capability is present and non-empty.

  Setaf          : String (bounded, max MAX_CAPABILITY_STRING_LENGTH characters)
    -- Raw value of the `setaf` string capability, or empty string when absent.

  Setab          : String (bounded, max MAX_CAPABILITY_STRING_LENGTH characters)
    -- Raw value of the `setab` string capability, or empty string when absent.

  Has_RGB_Flag   : Boolean
    -- True when the extended capability `RGB` (truecolor flag) is present and set.
    -- This flag appears in tmux-style terminfo extensions and signals that the terminal
    -- uses direct RGB (24-bit) colour for setaf/setab sequences.

  Has_Tc_Flag    : Boolean
    -- True when the extended capability `Tc` (truecolor flag used by some terminals
    -- including tmux itself and foot) is present and set.

  Term_Name      : String (bounded, max MAX_TERM_NAME_LENGTH characters)
    -- Primary terminal name extracted from the names section of the terminfo entry.

MAX_CAPABILITY_STRING_LENGTH shall be at least 64. MAX_TERM_NAME_LENGTH shall be at
least 64.

The Terminfo_Snapshot type shall carry the annotation SPARK_Mode => On and shall be
declared in a package spec that is fully SPARK-provable.
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
Restricting the snapshot to the five capabilities of interest (colors, setaf, setab, RGB,
Tc) avoids the overhead of representing the full terminfo capability set (ncurses defines
several hundred capabilities). These five are the only terminfo capabilities that the
Termicap color cascade consults. Recording Has_Setaf/Has_Setab as explicit booleans
alongside the string values simplifies callers: they do not need to test for empty string.
The -1/-2 sentinel convention for absent/cancelled numeric capabilities follows the ncurses
specification (ABSENT_NUMERIC = -1, CANCELLED_NUMERIC = -2) so that the distinction
between "database doesn't mention this capability" and "database explicitly disables this
capability" is preserved at the type level rather than collapsed into a single zero.
Bounded strings are required for SPARK provability (unbounded strings involve heap
allocation and dynamic dispatch, both outside the SPARK subset).
<<<

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-TIF-002
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Must
TITLE: Terminfo_Result Error Enumeration
STATEMENT: >>>
The library shall provide a result type Terminfo_Result that wraps either a
Terminfo_Snapshot (on success) or one of the following error codes (on failure):

  Error_No_Term
    -- The TERM environment variable is not set or is empty.

  Error_File_Not_Found
    -- No terminfo file was found for the current TERM value in any searched directory.

  Error_IO_Failure
    -- The terminfo file was found but could not be read (permissions, I/O error).

  Error_Invalid_Magic
    -- The file's first two bytes do not match a recognised terminfo magic number
    -- (0x011A for legacy format, 0x021E for extended-numeric format).

  Error_Header_Corrupt
    -- The header section sizes are internally inconsistent or cause an out-of-bounds
    -- access into the file data.

  Error_File_Too_Large
    -- The file size exceeds MAX_TERMINFO_FILE_SIZE and is rejected as a safety guard.

  Error_Encoding
    -- A string capability contains bytes outside the expected range.

No operation in the Terminfo feature shall raise an Ada exception. All error conditions
shall be represented by a Terminfo_Result error variant. Callers shall test the result
discriminant before accessing the snapshot value.

MAX_TERMINFO_FILE_SIZE shall be at least 32 768 bytes (32 KiB) and shall be a named
constant declared in the Terminfo package spec so that callers can reason about the bound.
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
A disjoint result type (rather than raising exceptions) is the established Termicap
convention for all fallible operations and is required for SPARK Silver provability.
The error enumeration is exhaustive by design: each error code maps to a distinct failure
mode that a caller may want to handle differently. For example, Error_No_Term and
Error_File_Not_Found are expected conditions in many environments (containers, minimal
chroot environments, CI systems without terminfo packages) and should be silently ignored
by the cascade; Error_Invalid_Magic and Error_Header_Corrupt indicate a corrupt or
foreign-format file and may warrant a diagnostic log entry. Bounding file size at 32 KiB
provides a SPARK-provable upper bound on the byte array used for parsing; the largest
known real terminfo file (rxvt-unicode with extensions) is under 8 KiB.
<<<

[/SECTION]

[SECTION]
TITLE: Search Path Resolution

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-TIF-003
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Must
TITLE: TERM Environment Variable Read
STATEMENT: >>>
Before any file system access, the Terminfo feature shall read the TERM environment
variable from the caller-supplied Environment snapshot (FUNC-ENV-001). If TERM is not
present in the snapshot (FUNC-ENV-002) or its value is the empty string, the feature shall
return Error_No_Term immediately without performing any file system search.

The TERM value shall be used exactly as retrieved from the snapshot with no case folding,
no whitespace trimming, and no validation beyond checking for empty string. The value may
contain hyphens (e.g., "xterm-256color") and digits; it shall not be expected to be a
valid file name component on all platforms.
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
Reading TERM from the Environment snapshot rather than from the live process environment
is the Termicap convention: the snapshot was captured at program start and is immutable,
making the entire detection cascade deterministic and testable without modifying the
process environment. Rejecting empty TERM before any I/O is correct: an empty TERM is
ambiguous (it usually means the program is running without a controlling terminal, e.g.
in a pipeline or cron job) and there is no meaningful terminfo entry to look up.
Case folding is intentionally absent: TERM values are case-sensitive on Unix file systems;
lowercasing "XTERM" would produce a wrong path on case-sensitive systems.
<<<

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-TIF-004
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Must
TITLE: Standard Search Directory Order
STATEMENT: >>>
The Terminfo feature shall search for the terminfo file by consulting the following
directories in the order listed, stopping at the first directory that yields a readable
file:

  1. The directory named by the TERMINFO environment variable (if set and non-empty).
  2. Each colon-separated directory listed in the TERMINFO_DIRS environment variable
     (if set and non-empty), processed left to right.
  3. The directory ~/.terminfo (where ~ is expanded to the value of the HOME environment
     variable; if HOME is not set, this entry is skipped).
  4. /usr/share/terminfo
  5. /etc/terminfo
  6. /lib/terminfo

If none of the directories yields a readable file, the feature shall return
Error_File_Not_Found.

The feature shall not follow symbolic links that resolve to paths outside the searched
directory (i.e., it shall use the OS-level open/read operations which follow symlinks by
default; no special symlink filtering is required). The feature shall not create, modify,
or delete any file or directory during the search.
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
This search order is the one documented by the ncurses(3X) manual and implemented by
ncurses, termenv (Go), and blessed (Node.js). Honouring $TERMINFO first gives the user
or application full override capability (useful in containers or when testing with a
custom terminfo database). $TERMINFO_DIRS (colon-separated, like PATH) is the ncurses
mechanism for adding multiple extra search roots. ~/.terminfo is the per-user override.
The three system directories (/usr/share/terminfo, /etc/terminfo, /lib/terminfo) cover
the installation paths used by Debian/Ubuntu, Red Hat/Fedora, Arch Linux, macOS
Homebrew, and FreeBSD respectively. Stopping at the first match mirrors ncurses behaviour
and prevents a corrupt entry in a higher-priority directory from being silently superseded
by a valid one lower in the hierarchy (if the file is found but corrupt, the error is
surfaced).
<<<

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-TIF-005
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Must
TITLE: Terminfo File Path Construction
STATEMENT: >>>
For each candidate directory D and a TERM value T, the Terminfo feature shall attempt
to construct and probe the following two file paths, in order:

  Primary path:   D / T(1) / T
    where T(1) is the single-character string consisting of the first character of T.

  Alternate path: D / HH / T
    where HH is the two-character lowercase hexadecimal representation of the ASCII
    (or Latin-1) code of the first character of T (e.g., "78" for 'x' = 0x78).

The feature shall attempt to open the Primary path first. Only if that path does not
exist or is not readable shall it attempt the Alternate path. If both paths within a
directory fail, the feature shall proceed to the next candidate directory (FUNC-TIF-004).

The constructed path strings shall not exceed MAX_PATH_LENGTH characters. If path
construction would exceed this limit, that candidate shall be skipped without error.
MAX_PATH_LENGTH shall be at least 512 and shall be a named constant.
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
The two path layouts reflect historical divergence in the Unix ecosystem. The Primary
layout (<dir>/<first-char>/<TERM>) is used by Linux (ncurses default), macOS, and most
modern BSDs. The Alternate layout (<dir>/<two-hex-digits>/<TERM>) was used by older
System V installations, some Solaris versions, and OpenBSD until relatively recently.
Supporting both layouts in priority order (primary then alternate) ensures compatibility
with the full range of Unix systems without requiring build-time configuration. Bounding
the path length at 512 characters is a SPARK safety guard: the path construction is done
in a fixed-size buffer, and any TERM value that would overflow the buffer almost certainly
denotes a misconfigured environment rather than a real terminal.
<<<

[/SECTION]

[SECTION]
TITLE: File Loading

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-TIF-006
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Must
TITLE: Terminfo File Read into Byte Array
STATEMENT: >>>
The Terminfo feature shall provide an operation that opens a terminfo file at a given
path and reads its entire contents into a caller-supplied fixed-size byte array. Its
representative signature is:

  procedure Read_File
     (Path       :     String;
      Buffer     : out Byte_Array;
      Size       : out Natural;
      Error      : out Read_Error);

where Read_Error is a discrete type with values: Read_OK, Read_Not_Found,
Read_IO_Error, Read_Too_Large.

The operation shall:
  1. Attempt to open the file at Path in read-only mode.
  2. If the file does not exist or cannot be opened, set Error := Read_Not_Found and
     return; Buffer and Size are unspecified.
  3. Read up to MAX_TERMINFO_FILE_SIZE bytes into Buffer. If the file size exceeds
     MAX_TERMINFO_FILE_SIZE, set Error := Read_Too_Large and close the file before
     returning.
  4. On a successful read, set Size to the number of bytes read and Error := Read_OK.
  5. On any I/O error during reading, set Error := Read_IO_Error, set Size := 0, and
     close the file.
  6. Always close the file descriptor before returning, regardless of error status.

Read_File shall be declared with SPARK_Mode => Off because it calls POSIX open/read/close
system calls via Ada FFI. The Byte_Array type and the Read_Error type shall be declared
in a SPARK-visible package so that callers with SPARK_Mode => On can reference them.
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
Loading the entire file into a bounded byte array before parsing is the approach used by
notcurses and blessed; it simplifies the parser significantly because all offset
calculations can be performed against a fixed buffer with known bounds, making them
trivially SPARK-provable. The alternative — streaming reads during parsing — would
require tracking file position as additional parser state and would complicate the
pre/post contracts. The MAX_TERMINFO_FILE_SIZE bound (32 KiB, defined in FUNC-TIF-002)
ensures that the buffer is stack-allocatable. Read_File is placed in an FFI package
(SPARK_Mode => Off) because Ada.Sequential_IO and POSIX file descriptors both involve OS
calls that are outside the SPARK language subset. The Always-close guarantee prevents
file descriptor leaks in error paths, which is especially important because the search
loop (FUNC-TIF-004) may attempt several paths before succeeding.
<<<

[/SECTION]

[SECTION]
TITLE: Binary Format Parsing — Header

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-TIF-007
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Must
TITLE: Magic Number Validation and Format Detection
STATEMENT: >>>
The Terminfo binary parser shall begin by inspecting the first two bytes of the file
buffer (bytes at offsets 0 and 1, little-endian 16-bit value) to determine the format
variant:

  0x011A  (decimal 282)  — Legacy ncurses format; numeric capabilities are 16-bit
                           signed integers.
  0x021E  (decimal 542)  — Extended-numeric ncurses format; numeric capabilities are
                           32-bit signed integers.

Any other value shall cause the parser to return Error_Invalid_Magic immediately,
without reading any further bytes.

The magic number comparison shall be a pure function declared with SPARK_Mode => On:

  function Detect_Format (Buffer : Byte_Array; Size : Natural) return Terminfo_Format;

where Terminfo_Format is an enumeration: (Legacy_16bit, Extended_32bit, Unknown).

The function shall carry the contract:
  Pre  => Size >= 2 and then Size <= Buffer'Length
  Post => (if Detect_Format'Result = Unknown
           then True
           else Detect_Format'Result in Legacy_16bit | Extended_32bit)
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
Checking the magic number first is the canonical safety gate for binary parsers: it
rejects foreign files (ELF binaries, compiled groff outputs, arbitrary binary data in
/usr/share) before any offset arithmetic. The two magic values (0x011A and 0x021E) are
documented in the ncurses term(5) man page and in the ncurses source
(ncurses/tinfo/read_entry.c). Both are stored little-endian; on big-endian systems the
byte-swap must be performed explicitly by the parser. The 16-bit legacy format is
universal and produced by all ncurses versions. The 32-bit extended-numeric format was
introduced in ncurses 6.1 (2018) to support terminals with more than 32 767 colors; it
is increasingly common (Arch Linux ships ncurses 6.4+ which generates 32-bit databases
by default). Detecting both ensures correctness on modern systems without breaking
compatibility with older installations.
<<<

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-TIF-008
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Must
TITLE: Header Section Parsing and Bounds Validation
STATEMENT: >>>
After magic number validation (FUNC-TIF-007), the parser shall read the fixed-size
header that immediately follows the magic bytes. The header contains five 16-bit
signed integer fields (little-endian), at byte offsets 2, 4, 6, 8, and 10 respectively:

  Names_Size      — Length in bytes of the names section (includes trailing NUL).
  Bool_Count      — Number of boolean capabilities.
  Num_Count       — Number of numeric capabilities.
  String_Count    — Number of string capability offset entries.
  Table_Size      — Length in bytes of the string data table.

The header fields shall be validated as follows before any section data is accessed:

  1. Names_Size >= 1 and Names_Size <= MAX_NAMES_SECTION_SIZE.
  2. Bool_Count >= 0 and Bool_Count <= MAX_BOOL_COUNT.
  3. Num_Count >= 0 and Num_Count <= MAX_NUM_COUNT.
  4. String_Count >= 0 and String_Count <= MAX_STRING_COUNT.
  5. Table_Size >= 0 and Table_Size <= MAX_STRING_TABLE_SIZE.
  6. The computed total consumed size (12 + Names_Size + Bool_Count + padding +
     Num_Size * Num_Count + 2 * String_Count + Table_Size) shall not exceed the
     actual file size (Size parameter from FUNC-TIF-006).

If any validation fails, the parser shall return Error_Header_Corrupt.

Padding: after the names and boolean sections, a single alignment byte is inserted if
(Names_Size + Bool_Count) is odd, to align the subsequent numeric section to a 16-bit
boundary.

MAX_NAMES_SECTION_SIZE shall be 512. MAX_BOOL_COUNT shall be 64. MAX_NUM_COUNT shall be
512. MAX_STRING_COUNT shall be 512. MAX_STRING_TABLE_SIZE shall be 16 384 (16 KiB).
These named constants shall be declared in the Terminfo package spec.

Num_Size is 2 for Legacy_16bit format and 4 for Extended_32bit format.

The header parser shall be declared with SPARK_Mode => On and shall carry pre/post
contracts asserting that on success all computed section offsets are within 0 .. Size - 1.
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
The header layout is defined in the ncurses term(5) manual. The total-consumed-size check
(validation rule 6) is the critical safety property: without it, a crafted or corrupt
file could cause the parser to compute section offsets that point outside the loaded
buffer, which in Ada would raise Constraint_Error (an index check). The SPARK prover can
discharge the absence of Constraint_Error only if the contracts assert the bounds
explicitly. The named MAX_* constants serve two roles: they make the validation rules
readable, and they provide the SPARK prover with loop invariant material. The alignment
padding after the boolean section is a subtlety noted in the ncurses source and term(5):
it ensures that the numeric section starts on a 2-byte (or 4-byte) boundary, which
matters for direct memory access in C; in Ada we always read byte-by-byte and reconstruct
integers, so alignment is only relevant for computing the correct offset.
<<<

[/SECTION]

[SECTION]
TITLE: Binary Format Parsing — Capability Sections

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-TIF-009
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Must
TITLE: Boolean Capability Extraction by Index
STATEMENT: >>>
The Terminfo feature shall provide a pure function to extract a single boolean capability
value by its standard ncurses index. Its representative signature is:

  function Get_Boolean
     (Buffer  : Byte_Array;
      Header  : Parsed_Header;
      Index   : Natural)
      return Boolean_Cap_Value;

where Boolean_Cap_Value is a discrete type: (Absent, Cancelled, True_Value, False_Value).
A byte value of 1 maps to True_Value. A byte value of 0 maps to False_Value. A byte
value of 16#FF# (CANCELLED_BOOLEAN, decimal 255) maps to Cancelled. A byte value of
16#FE# (ABSENT_BOOLEAN, decimal 254) maps to Absent. Any other byte value maps to
Absent.

The function shall:
  1. Verify that Index < Header.Bool_Count. If not, return Absent.
  2. Read the byte at Buffer (Bool_Section_Offset + Index).
  3. Return the Boolean_Cap_Value corresponding to the byte (as above).

Get_Boolean shall be declared with SPARK_Mode => On and shall carry the contract:
  Pre => Header_Is_Valid (Buffer, Header)
         and then Bool_Section_Offset + Header.Bool_Count <= Buffer'Length

where Header_Is_Valid is a ghost function that asserts the invariants established by
FUNC-TIF-008.
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
Boolean capabilities are the simplest section: each capability is represented by exactly
one byte at a known offset. The standard ncurses boolean capability set defines
approximately 44 capabilities (terminfo(5)); Bool_Count may be less than this on trimmed
databases. The four-value enumeration (Absent, Cancelled, True_Value, False_Value) maps
directly to the ncurses conventions (ABSENT_BOOLEAN = 0xFF, CANCELLED_BOOLEAN = 0xFE,
documented in term.h). While the primary Termicap use case does not need boolean
capabilities from the standard section (the capabilities of interest — RGB and Tc — are
in the extended section), providing a general Get_Boolean function allows the feature to
be extended in the future. The ghost predicate Header_Is_Valid concentrates the bounds
invariants in one place, preventing contract duplication across all capability extraction
functions.
<<<

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-TIF-010
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Must
TITLE: Numeric Capability Extraction by Index
STATEMENT: >>>
The Terminfo feature shall provide a pure function to extract a single numeric capability
value by its standard ncurses index. Its representative signature is:

  function Get_Numeric
     (Buffer  : Byte_Array;
      Header  : Parsed_Header;
      Format  : Terminfo_Format;
      Index   : Natural)
      return Integer;

The function shall:
  1. Verify that Index < Header.Num_Count. If not, return ABSENT_NUMERIC (-1).
  2. Compute the byte offset of the capability within the numeric section:
       Offset := Num_Section_Offset + Index * Num_Size
     where Num_Size is 2 for Legacy_16bit format and 4 for Extended_32bit format.
  3. Verify that Offset + Num_Size - 1 < Buffer'Length. If not, return ABSENT_NUMERIC.
  4. Read Num_Size bytes from Buffer starting at Offset, interpreting them as a
     little-endian signed integer (16-bit for Legacy_16bit, 32-bit for Extended_32bit).
  5. Return the integer value as-is. The ncurses sentinel values ABSENT_NUMERIC (-1)
     and CANCELLED_NUMERIC (-2) are passed through unmodified.

ABSENT_NUMERIC and CANCELLED_NUMERIC shall be named constants declared in the package
spec with values -1 and -2 respectively.

Get_Numeric shall be declared with SPARK_Mode => On and shall carry the contract:
  Pre  => Header_Is_Valid (Buffer, Header) and Format /= Unknown
  Post => Get_Numeric'Result >= -2

The `colors` capability has standard ncurses index 13. This index shall be declared as a
named constant COLORS_INDEX with value 13 in the package spec.
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
The `colors` capability is the single most important terminfo numeric for Termicap: it
directly encodes the maximum number of colors the terminal claims to support (e.g., 8, 16,
256, or very large values for truecolor). Its standard index (13) is defined in
ncurses/include/Caps and is stable across all ncurses versions. The little-endian byte
order for numeric fields is mandated by the ncurses term(5) specification regardless of
the host byte order; the parser must always reconstruct integers from bytes in
little-endian order and not rely on platform byte order. The postcondition
(result >= -2) establishes the lower bound on the returned value, which allows callers
in SPARK to reason about the comparison result without knowing the full integer range.
<<<

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-TIF-011
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Must
TITLE: String Capability Extraction by Index
STATEMENT: >>>
The Terminfo feature shall provide a pure function to extract a single string capability
value by its standard ncurses index. Its representative signature is:

  function Get_String
     (Buffer  : Byte_Array;
      Header  : Parsed_Header;
      Index   : Natural;
      Result  : out Bounded_String;
      Present : out Boolean);

where Bounded_String is a fixed-capacity string type (capacity MAX_CAPABILITY_STRING_LENGTH,
as defined in FUNC-TIF-001). Present shall be set to False when the capability is absent
or cancelled.

The function shall:
  1. Verify that Index < Header.String_Count. If not, set Present := False and return.
  2. Compute the byte offset of the string offset entry within the string offset table:
       Entry_Offset := String_Table_Offset + Index * 2
  3. Read the 16-bit little-endian signed integer at Entry_Offset. This is the string's
     offset within the string data table. If the value is -1 (ABSENT_STRING) or -2
     (CANCELLED_STRING), set Present := False and return.
  4. Verify that String_Data_Offset + Offset < Buffer'Length. If not, set Present := False
     and return.
  5. Copy bytes from Buffer starting at (String_Data_Offset + Offset) until a NUL byte
     (0x00) is encountered or MAX_CAPABILITY_STRING_LENGTH bytes have been copied,
     whichever comes first.
  6. Set Result to the copied bytes and Present := True.

The standard ncurses indices for the target capabilities shall be declared as named
constants:
  SETAF_INDEX : constant := 359;   -- set ANSI foreground color
  SETAB_INDEX : constant := 360;   -- set ANSI background color

Get_String shall be declared with SPARK_Mode => On and shall carry the contract:
  Pre => Header_Is_Valid (Buffer, Header)
  Post => (if not Present then Result'Length = 0)
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
String capabilities in terminfo are stored as NUL-terminated strings in a contiguous
string data table; the string offset table (also called the string offset array) maps
capability indices to byte offsets within that table. The two-level indirection (index
→ offset entry → string data) is the standard ncurses layout. SETAF_INDEX = 359 and
SETAB_INDEX = 360 are the stable ncurses capability numbers for `set_a_foreground` and
`set_a_background`; they are defined in ncurses/include/Caps and have not changed since
ncurses 5.x. Using named constants rather than inline integer literals prevents
transcription errors and documents the capability identity. The NUL-termination and
length-bound dual stopping condition is a standard safe-string-copy pattern that is
easily SPARK-provable via a loop invariant asserting the copy index stays within bounds.
<<<

[/SECTION]

[SECTION]
TITLE: Extended Capabilities Section

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-TIF-012
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Must
TITLE: Extended Section Detection and Header Parsing
STATEMENT: >>>
After the five standard sections have been parsed, the Terminfo feature shall check
whether the file contains an extended capabilities section. The extended section is
present if and only if there are bytes remaining after the end of the standard string
data table and those remaining bytes include a valid extended header.

The extended section header has the same structure as the main header but with its own
five 16-bit signed fields (at the start of the extended section):

  Ext_Bool_Count    — Number of extended boolean capabilities.
  Ext_Num_Count     — Number of extended numeric capabilities.
  Ext_String_Count  — Number of extended string capabilities (includes capability names).
  Ext_String_Entries — Number of string offset entries.
  Ext_Table_Size    — Size in bytes of the extended string data table.

The extended header shall be validated with the same bounds checks as the main header
(FUNC-TIF-008), substituting the extended section's MAX_* values:
  Ext_Bool_Count <= 64, Ext_Num_Count <= 128, Ext_String_Count <= 256,
  Ext_Table_Size <= 8 192.

If the extended section is absent or its header is invalid, the parser shall set
Has_RGB_Flag := False and Has_Tc_Flag := False in the Terminfo_Snapshot and return
success; the absence of extended capabilities is not an error.

The extended section parser shall be declared with SPARK_Mode => On and shall carry
a pre-condition asserting that the extended section start offset is within the buffer.
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
The extended capabilities section is a ncurses extension (documented in term(5) under
"USER-DEFINED CAPABILITIES") that allows terminal vendors and configuration authors to
define capabilities beyond the standard set. It is the mechanism by which the `RGB` and
`Tc` truecolor flags are encoded. Not all terminfo entries have an extended section;
standard xterm entries do not, while tmux, wezterm, and foot entries do. Treating its
absence as a non-error (rather than Error_Header_Corrupt) is essential: the majority of
terminfo entries on a typical system will not have extended sections. The extended header
MAX_* bounds are tighter than the main section bounds because extended capabilities are
by convention few in number; a file with thousands of extended capabilities would be
malformed.
<<<

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-TIF-013
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Must
TITLE: Extended Capability Name Resolution
STATEMENT: >>>
Within the extended section, capability names are stored as NUL-terminated strings in
the extended string data table. The layout of the extended section is:

  1. Extended boolean values: Ext_Bool_Count bytes (one byte per boolean capability).
  2. Alignment pad: one byte if (Ext_Bool_Count + Ext_Num_Count) is odd.
  3. Extended numeric values: Ext_Num_Count * Num_Size bytes.
  4. Extended string offset table: Ext_String_Entries * 2 bytes (16-bit offsets into
     extended string data table, for both capability string values and capability names).
  5. Extended string data table: Ext_Table_Size bytes.

Within the string offset table, the first (Ext_String_Count - Ext_Bool_Count -
Ext_Num_Count) entries are offsets to string capability values, and the remaining
Ext_Bool_Count + Ext_Num_Count + (Ext_String_Count - ...) entries are offsets to
capability name strings, in the same order as the values.

The Terminfo feature shall resolve capability names by iterating over the name entries
and comparing each NUL-terminated name string against the target name strings "RGB"
and "Tc" (case-sensitive, exact match). The iteration shall be bounded by Ext_String_Count.

Name resolution shall be implemented as a bounded loop with a SPARK loop invariant
asserting that the name index remains within 0 .. Ext_String_Count - 1.
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
The extended section layout is the most complex aspect of the terminfo binary format and
is not documented in term(5) itself — it is documented only in the ncurses source code
(ncurses/tinfo/read_entry.c). The key detail is that capability name strings are stored
in the same string data table as capability value strings; the order of name entries in
the offset table mirrors the order of value entries. To determine the boolean value of
"RGB", the parser must: (1) find the offset entry for "RGB" in the name section of the
offset table, (2) determine that "RGB" corresponds to a boolean capability (its position
in the combined name list falls within the first Ext_Bool_Count entries), and (3) read
the byte from the extended boolean section at the corresponding boolean index. Case-
sensitive comparison is correct: "RGB" and "Tc" are defined with this exact capitalisation
in tmux's terminfo source and in the ncurses terminfo database.
<<<

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-TIF-014
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Must
TITLE: RGB and Tc Truecolor Flag Extraction
STATEMENT: >>>
The Terminfo feature shall extract the `RGB` and `Tc` extended capability flags as
follows:

  RGB flag: The extended capability named "RGB" (case-sensitive) may appear as either
    a boolean capability (byte value 1 = True) or a numeric capability (value >= 1).
    When found as a boolean with value True_Value, set Has_RGB_Flag := True.
    When found as a numeric with value >= 1, set Has_RGB_Flag := True.
    When absent, cancelled, or has boolean value False_Value or numeric value 0,
    set Has_RGB_Flag := False.

  Tc flag: The extended capability named "Tc" (case-sensitive) may appear as a boolean
    capability (byte value 1 = True) or as a string capability (any non-empty value).
    When found as a boolean with value True_Value, set Has_Tc_Flag := True.
    When found as a string capability with non-empty value, set Has_Tc_Flag := True.
    When absent, cancelled, has boolean value False_Value, or has empty string value,
    set Has_Tc_Flag := False.

If neither "RGB" nor "Tc" is found in the extended section, both Has_RGB_Flag and
Has_Tc_Flag shall be False in the resulting Terminfo_Snapshot.

The extraction shall be a pure function declared with SPARK_Mode => On:

  procedure Extract_Truecolor_Flags
     (Buffer    :     Byte_Array;
      Header    :     Parsed_Header;
      Ext       :     Extended_Header;
      Format    :     Terminfo_Format;
      Has_RGB   : out Boolean;
      Has_Tc    : out Boolean);

with the contract:
  Pre => Header_Is_Valid (Buffer, Header)
         and then Extended_Is_Valid (Buffer, Header, Ext)
         and then Format /= Unknown
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
The RGB and Tc flags are the two terminfo-derived indicators of 24-bit truecolor support.
They were introduced by the terminal emulator community to address the gap in the standard
terminfo capability set, which has no defined boolean for truecolor. "RGB" was introduced
by ncurses author Thomas Dickey and is present in ncurses's own terminfo database for
terminals such as xterm with direct-color support. "Tc" was introduced by tmux to mark
terminals capable of direct-colour sequences in the tmux terminfo entry and is now used
by foot, wezterm, and others. Accepting RGB as either a boolean or a numeric (both
representations appear in the wild), and Tc as either a boolean or a string, provides
maximum compatibility with the diverse terminfo databases deployed on real systems.
References: tmux FAQ "How do I use a 256 colour terminal"; ncurses FAQ "Is there a way
to turn on the RGB capability?"; blessed source (lib/tput.js, _truecolor() function).
<<<

[/SECTION]

[SECTION]
TITLE: Top-Level Parse Entry Point

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-TIF-015
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Must
TITLE: Parse_Terminfo Entry Function
STATEMENT: >>>
The Terminfo feature shall provide a top-level function that performs the complete
terminfo lookup and parsing pipeline and returns a Terminfo_Result. Its representative
signature is:

  function Parse_Terminfo (Env : Environment) return Terminfo_Result;

The function shall execute the following steps in order:

  1. Read TERM from Env (FUNC-TIF-003). On empty/absent TERM, return Error_No_Term.
  2. Build the ordered list of candidate directories (FUNC-TIF-004).
  3. For each candidate directory, construct the Primary and Alternate paths
     (FUNC-TIF-005) and attempt Read_File (FUNC-TIF-006). On Read_Not_Found, continue
     to the next candidate. On Read_IO_Error or Read_Too_Large, continue to the next
     candidate (non-fatal I/O errors on individual paths do not abort the search).
  4. On the first successful Read_File, call Parse_Header (FUNC-TIF-008). On
     Error_Header_Corrupt or Error_Invalid_Magic, return that error immediately (a file
     was found but is corrupt — do not fall back to the next candidate).
  5. Extract the `colors` numeric (FUNC-TIF-010, index COLORS_INDEX).
  6. Extract the `setaf` string (FUNC-TIF-011, index SETAF_INDEX).
  7. Extract the `setab` string (FUNC-TIF-011, index SETAB_INDEX).
  8. Attempt to parse the extended section (FUNC-TIF-012). If absent or header invalid,
     treat as Has_RGB_Flag = False, Has_Tc_Flag = False (no error).
  9. If extended section is valid, extract RGB and Tc flags (FUNC-TIF-014).
  10. Construct and return a Terminfo_Result containing the populated Terminfo_Snapshot.

If no candidate directory yields a readable file, return Error_File_Not_Found.

Parse_Terminfo shall be callable from SPARK_Mode => On code. Its body may be annotated
SPARK_Mode => Off only if it contains calls to the FFI Read_File operation; in that case,
a thin SPARK_Mode => On wrapper that delegates to the Off body shall be provided so that
callers with SPARK contracts can reference the function.
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
Parse_Terminfo is the single public entry point for the feature; all other functions
are implementation details. This single-entry design keeps the public API minimal and
consistent with the Termicap convention of one function per detection concern (e.g.,
Detect_Color_Level, Detect_Terminal_Id). Step 4's behaviour of returning corruption
errors immediately rather than falling back to the next candidate is deliberate: if a
terminfo file for TERM was found but is corrupt, falling back silently to a lower-priority
directory (which likely contains a different — possibly wrong — terminal entry) would be
more confusing than surfacing the error. The separation between the FFI Read_File call
(SPARK_Mode => Off) and the pure parsing functions (SPARK_Mode => On) mirrors the pattern
established by the OSC Query Infrastructure (FUNC-OSC-015) and keeps the maximum SPARK
coverage over the parsing logic.
<<<

[/SECTION]

[SECTION]
TITLE: Immutability and Snapshot Semantics

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-TIF-016
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Must
TITLE: Immutable Parsed Snapshot
STATEMENT: >>>
The Terminfo_Snapshot record (FUNC-TIF-001) shall be an immutable value type. After
Parse_Terminfo (FUNC-TIF-015) returns a successful Terminfo_Result, the Terminfo_Snapshot
within that result shall not be modifiable by the caller or by any subsequent Termicap
operation. The type shall not expose any procedure or function with an in out or out
parameter of type Terminfo_Snapshot or any component thereof.

The Terminfo_Snapshot type shall not be a tagged type, a limited type, or a controlled
type. It shall be a plain Ada record type suitable for value-copy semantics.

Parse_Terminfo shall not cache its result or maintain any global state. Each call to
Parse_Terminfo performs a fresh file search and parse and returns an independent
Terminfo_Snapshot. Callers that require repeated access to the parsed data shall retain
the returned Terminfo_Result value themselves.
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
Value-copy semantics for the snapshot align with the Termicap architectural principle
(established for the Terminal_Capabilities record and the Environment snapshot) that all
detection results are immutable values, never shared mutable objects. Avoiding caching
and global state in Parse_Terminfo keeps the function referentially transparent (modulo
the file system) and makes it trivially thread-safe: concurrent calls from different
tasks each get their own independent result without synchronisation. The prohibition on
tagged and controlled types keeps Terminfo_Snapshot within the SPARK language subset,
since Ada.Finalization.Controlled is not supported by GNATprove.
<<<

[/SECTION]

[SECTION]
TITLE: Integration with Color Detection Cascade

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-TIF-017
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Should
TITLE: Color Cascade Integration Point
STATEMENT: >>>
The color detection cascade shall consult the Terminfo_Snapshot as a passive source
after environment variable heuristics and before active terminal probing. The cascade
shall use the Terminfo_Snapshot as follows:

  1. If Snapshot.Colors >= 16_777_216 (2^24), infer at minimum Color_Level_TrueColor.
  2. If Snapshot.Has_RGB_Flag or Snapshot.Has_Tc_Flag, infer at minimum
     Color_Level_TrueColor regardless of Snapshot.Colors.
  3. If Snapshot.Colors >= 256 (and steps 1 and 2 do not apply), infer at minimum
     Color_Level_256.
  4. If Snapshot.Colors >= 8 (and steps 1-3 do not apply), infer at minimum
     Color_Level_16.
  5. If Snapshot.Colors = ABSENT_NUMERIC (-1) or CANCELLED_NUMERIC (-2), the terminfo
     source contributes no color level inference; proceed to the next cascade source.

The terminfo source shall be treated as an advisory input: a higher-priority source
(FORCE_COLOR, COLORTERM, TERM suffix matching) may override the terminfo-derived level
in either direction.

The integration logic shall reference the Terminfo_Snapshot by value (not by access type)
and shall be SPARK_Mode => On.
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
Placing terminfo after environment variables and before active probing reflects the
consensus from the reference frameworks analysis: environment variables are cheapest and
most portable, terminfo is a reliable but slower passive source (requires file I/O),
and active probing (OSC queries) is the most accurate but has side effects and latency.
The colors >= 2^24 threshold for truecolor follows the ncurses convention: terminals
that support direct-color report colors as 16777216 in their terminfo entries. The
RGB/Tc flag check as a separate condition is necessary because some terminals (e.g., foot
before 1.15) set the Tc flag but report colors = 256 in the standard numeric section.
The advisory semantics (higher-priority sources may override) preserves the overall
cascade's ability to honour FORCE_COLOR=0 (disable even if terminfo says truecolor) and
COLORTERM=truecolor (enable truecolor even if terminfo is absent).
<<<

[/SECTION]

[SECTION]
TITLE: SPARK Provability

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-TIF-018
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Must
TITLE: SPARK Silver Target for Binary Parser
STATEMENT: >>>
All parsing functions in the Terminfo feature — including Detect_Format (FUNC-TIF-007),
header parsing (FUNC-TIF-008), Get_Boolean (FUNC-TIF-009), Get_Numeric (FUNC-TIF-010),
Get_String (FUNC-TIF-011), extended section parsing (FUNC-TIF-012, FUNC-TIF-013), and
Extract_Truecolor_Flags (FUNC-TIF-014) — shall be declared with SPARK_Mode => On and
shall be provable at SPARK Silver level using GNATprove.

SPARK Silver provability requires at minimum:
  (a) No run-time exceptions: all array accesses guarded by pre-conditions or defensive
      index checks that the prover can discharge.
  (b) No infinite loops: all loops over byte arrays or capability sections shall have
      explicit loop variants declared with pragma Loop_Variant (Decreases => ...) or
      equivalent.
  (c) Pre/post contracts on all public subprograms as specified in FUNC-TIF-007 through
      FUNC-TIF-014.
  (d) Ghost functions Header_Is_Valid and Extended_Is_Valid to encapsulate structural
      invariants so that contracts remain readable.
  (e) No access types, no dynamic dispatch, no allocators, and no exceptions in any
      SPARK_Mode => On unit.

The Read_File operation (FUNC-TIF-006) and the Parse_Terminfo top-level function body
(FUNC-TIF-015, body only) shall be SPARK_Mode => Off. A thin SPARK_Mode => On
specification for Parse_Terminfo shall be provided so that callers may reference the
function in SPARK contracts.
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
SPARK Silver is the established target for all Termicap pure-logic components (consistent
with FUNC-OSC-010, FUNC-OSC-014, and the keyboard and mouse detection features). The
binary parser is an ideal candidate for SPARK Silver: it is purely functional (input byte
array → output record), has no I/O, no concurrency, and all loops are trivially bounded
by array sizes. The ghost function pattern (Header_Is_Valid, Extended_Is_Valid) is a
SPARK idiom for grouping related precondition clauses into a named predicate; GNATprove
inlines ghost functions during proof and they have zero run-time cost. Loop variants are
required for all loops that traverse the byte array or capability sections: without them
GNATprove cannot prove absence of non-termination (a Silver requirement). The
SPARK_Mode => Off annotation on Read_File is unavoidable due to Ada file I/O being
outside the SPARK subset; this mirrors the boundary established in FUNC-OSC-015.
<<<

[/SECTION]

[SECTION]
TITLE: Error Handling

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-TIF-019
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Must
TITLE: No Exception Propagation from Terminfo Operations
STATEMENT: >>>
No public subprogram in the Terminfo feature shall propagate an Ada exception to its
caller under any input condition, including:

  - TERM set to an arbitrarily long or unusual string.
  - Terminfo file containing malformed, truncated, or adversarially crafted content.
  - File system errors (permission denied, dangling symlink, I/O error on read).
  - Extended section with inconsistent or corrupt internal structure.
  - Buffer index computations that would, without guards, exceed buffer bounds.

All error conditions shall be reported via the Terminfo_Result type (FUNC-TIF-002) or,
for lower-level helpers, via out parameters of discrete error types. Constraint_Error,
Program_Error, Storage_Error, and Ada.IO_Exceptions.* shall not be allowed to propagate
to the caller.

The FFI Read_File operation (SPARK_Mode => Off) shall catch all I/O exceptions internally
and convert them to the Read_Error discrete type before returning.
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
The no-exception guarantee is the Termicap library-wide contract (established by
FUNC-ENV-001 and the OSC Query Infrastructure) and is required for SPARK Silver: a
subprogram with SPARK_Mode => On cannot propagate exceptions, because exception
propagation is outside the SPARK language semantics. For callers in the color detection
cascade that invoke Parse_Terminfo in a larger SPARK_Mode => On context, any exception
propagation from the terminfo layer would violate the cascade's own SPARK contracts. The
Read_File exception catch-and-convert pattern is the same one used by FUNC-OSC-001 for
the /dev/tty open operation.
<<<

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-TIF-020
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Should
TITLE: Graceful Handling of Missing terminfo Package
STATEMENT: >>>
The Terminfo feature shall treat the complete absence of terminfo data as a normal,
expected condition. When Parse_Terminfo returns Error_File_Not_Found, the calling code
in the color detection cascade shall log a diagnostic message at the Debug level (not
Warning or Error) and proceed to the next cascade source without aborting detection.

The Terminfo feature shall not make the presence of a terminfo database a requirement
for any Termicap operation. All other detection methods (environment variables, active
OSC probing, DECRPM queries) shall continue to function correctly when terminfo data
is unavailable.

Specifically, the following environments shall be handled gracefully without any user-
visible error:
  - Alpine Linux and other musl-libc containers (no ncurses-terminfo package installed).
  - Docker/OCI containers with minimal base images.
  - Systems where /usr/share/terminfo is absent or empty.
  - Any environment where the TERM value has no corresponding terminfo entry.
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
Container environments and CI systems frequently run without terminfo databases installed,
because they are not running interactive terminals and the terminfo package is considered
a non-essential dependency. Termicap is explicitly designed to work in such environments
(it is a detection library, not a terminal control library). Logging at Debug level rather
than Warning prevents noise in production deployments of applications that embed Termicap:
the absence of terminfo is not an error for the application, only a data point for the
detection cascade. This requirement reflects the recommendation from the global synthesis
(§7, point 2): "Start without terminfo (Phase 1-4). Add optional terminfo parsing as a
Tier 4 feature. Modern terminals are well-served by env var heuristics."
<<<

[/SECTION]
